              "textDisplay": "Time is a fundamental concept that underlies our understanding of the physical world, and it is difficult to define precisely. However, we can measure time by using a clock or other timekeeping device, and we can compare the results of different clocks to establish a standard for the passage of time.\r\u003cbr\u003e\r\u003cbr\u003eWhen we talk about time in the context of special relativity, we are referring to the way in which time is experienced by observers moving relative to each other. As you mentioned, when an observer moves at a high speed relative to another observer, they will perceive time differently. This is not just a matter of perception or measurementbut a fundamental difference in the way in which time is experienced due to the principles of relativity.\r\u003cbr\u003e\r\u003cbr\u003eThe slowing of a clock as it moves at high speeds is not just an artifact of our measurementbut a consequence of the way in which time is experienced by observers in different reference frames. This has been demonstrated through numerous experiments, such as the famous Hafele-Keating experiment in which atomic clocks were flown on airplanes to demonstrate the effects of relativity on timekeeping.\r\u003cbr\u003e\r\u003cbr\u003eTherefore, while a clock ticking may not be a representation of time itself, it is a useful tool for measuring the passage of time and for understanding the way in which time is experienced by observers in different reference frames.",
