          "snippet": {
            "videoId": "yuD34tEpRFw",
            "textDisplay": "I must take issue with Einstein&#39;s assertion that a uniformly moving light clock perpendicular to its height would appear to be cycling slower than a non-moving one, which was his whole basis for time dilation. Does it take longer for a ball to hit the floor when dropped inside a moving train than it does when the train is not moving? No it does not, it takes exactly the same amount of time. This is a well established fact of physics, going back to Galileo and Newton. It doesn&#39;t matter how fast you propel an object horizontally, it will hit the ground at exactly the same time as another object dropped straight down. How then is it plausible that we would see light in a moving light clock moving between the top and bottom slower than normal light speed? That would actually defy the concept of the constancy of light speed. \u003cbr\u003eEinstein actually violated one of his own postulates to try to support another of his postulates. \u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eAs the speed of falling objects clearly shows, vertical velocity is completely unaffected by horizontal velocity, even when it&#39;s physical objects, which are possible to impart a horizontal force and therefore velocity upon. You can&#39;t even impart horizontal velocity onto vertically propagating photons, because they have no mass. They don&#39;t even move vertically due to force being applied, it&#39;s just the rate of wave propagation, so how much less plausible is it that they&#39;re moving sideways when they were only ever propagating vertically? If they&#39;re not moving sideways, and they&#39;re obviously not, then how could they be moving diagonally, which is a combination of vertical and horizontal motion? Where&#39;s the postulate of sideways moving vertically propagating photons? I would be interested in seeing a quote of that.",
            "textOriginal": "I must take issue with Einstein's assertion that a uniformly moving light clock perpendicular to its height would appear to be cycling slower than a non-moving one, which was his whole basis for time dilation. Does it take longer for a ball to hit the floor when dropped inside a moving train than it does when the train is not moving? No it does not, it takes exactly the same amount of time. This is a well established fact of physics, going back to Galileo and Newton. It doesn't matter how fast you propel an object horizontally, it will hit the ground at exactly the same time as another object dropped straight down. How then is it plausible that we would see light in a moving light clock moving between the top and bottom slower than normal light speed? That would actually defy the concept of the constancy of light speed. \nEinstein actually violated one of his own postulates to try to support another of his postulates. \n\nAs the speed of falling objects clearly shows, vertical velocity is completely unaffected by horizontal velocity, even when it's physical objects, which are possible to impart a horizontal force and therefore velocity upon. You can't even impart horizontal velocity onto vertically propagating photons, because they have no mass. They don't even move vertically due to force being applied, it's just the rate of wave propagation, so how much less plausible is it that they're moving sideways when they were only ever propagating vertically? If they're not moving sideways, and they're obviously not, then how could they be moving diagonally, which is a combination of vertical and horizontal motion? Where's the postulate of sideways moving vertically propagating photons? I would be interested in seeing a quote of that.",
